      "SummaryText": "Global Advanced Metals USA, Inc. (GAM), located in Boyertown, PA, is committed to ensuring a safe work environment for our employees and the community.  To this end, the management actively supports the implementation of safe work procedures for all aspects of the operations, including the processing of the one regulated substance:  hydrofluoric acid (HF), 70% or less.  The facility follows the regulation and intent of the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency (U.S. EPA) Risk Management Program (RMP).\n\nThis facility utilizes HF as an integral component of the manufacturing operations of inorganic compounds and refining of nonferrous metals.  HF is delivered to the facility in tank trucks.  Delivered HF is unloaded into one of three bulk storage tanks.  During delivery, HF trucks are flange-connected at the unloading fill station and compressed air is used to off-load the acid.  At all points during delivery, a qualified facility employee and qualified personnel from the supplier remain with the delivery truck.  From the bulk HF storage tanks, measured quantities of HF are pumped into process vessels in four buildings.  During the transfer of HF to the process vessels, HF is added to water and the concentration of HF immediately drops below 50% by weight and is no longer regulated by RMP.\n\nAs part of the RMP requirements, facilities that contain a regulated substance (such as HF) at quantities exceeding the RMP threshold must consider the impact of a worst-case and an alternative-case release of the substance. GAM utilized the U.S. EPA RMP*Comp model and the U.S. EPA Offsite Consequence Analysis (OCA) Guidance reference tables and equations to determine the potential impacts of both release scenarios. The worst-case scenario is based on the largest single vessel containing HF (i.e., the bulk HF storage tank shared by Buildings 073 and 087) and assumes that the entire tank volume is released into the diked area surrounding the vessel. The alternative scenario assumes t"
    },
