      "ESSeqNum": 1,
      "FacilityID": 1000101318,
      "SummaryText": "hat 173 pounds of HF is released through a pipe leak during a HF truck unloading event into an unmitigated area. U.S. EPA's MARPLOT software and other publicly-available resources were utilized to update the residential population and the public and environmental receptors for the 2023 OCA.\n\nUpdate November 2023: GAM intends to fill the second bulk HF storage tank that is shared by Buildings 073 and 087, which was previously installed but remained empty when the 2023 RMP 5-Year Resubmission was submitted. The two bulk HF tanks shared by these buildings are identical in size and have identical, but separate, containment areas. There is no interconnection between the two tanks that would increase the maximum single-vessel quantity release that was used for the 2023 OCA worst-case scenario. In addition, GAM has reviewed the alternative release scenario and has determined that this scenario also will not change as a result of filling the second bulk HF tank. The processes associated with Buildings 073 and 087 have been updated to reflect the new total amount of HF associated with each building, equal to the volume of both bulk HF tanks. The increased storage volume of HF does not change the Facility's program level since the processes associated with Buildings 073 and 087 were already Program Level 3 processes prior to this change.\n\nAs part of this facility's commitment to provide a safe work environment, GAM has implemented a number of programs to enhance safety.  Pertinent PSM & RMP information is communicated to plant personnel weekly to review plant safety, health and environmental issues.  General awareness HF training is given to all employees and contractors.  Operators of HF systems receive additional site-specific training.  Components of HF systems are covered under a Mechanical Integrity program to assure that they operate safely and are physically sound.  Appropriately detailed standard operating procedures (work instructions) are in place for start-up and s"
