      "SummaryText": "hutdown of the processes in both normal and emergency situations.  Information on chemicals, process technology, and equipment has been compiled.  Changes to the processes are reviewed under Management of Change procedures.  Pre-Start Safety Reviews are conducted prior to the implementation of any process change. Contractors receive extensive safety training prior to beginning work in the facility and receive additional site-specific safety training for their assigned work area.  Competence of contractors is assured as part of the contractor selection process.  Hot work and other safe work permit programs are in place in the facility.  Process Hazard Analyses using the HAZOP methodology are conducted to identify potential hazards and areas for improvement.  Any incidents are investigated to determine the root cause and identify changes to prevent recurrence.  The Risk Management Program is outlined and discussed in a PSM/RMP program document in use at the facility.\n  \nGAM demonstrates its commitment to public and worker safety through a continuous accident prevention program and active participation in the OSHA VPP STAR program.  All incidents and near misses are reported and investigated to identify root causes with corrective actions directed at preventing reoccurrence.  Investigation results are communicated to all on-site employees and contractors for awareness.  GAM has an Emergency Action Plan (EAP) to assure safe response to incidents involving HF and other chemicals.  The EAP is reviewed and updated when a significant change to a chemical system occurs.  All employees and contractors are trained on the notification and evacuation procedures detailed in the EAP.  GAM maintains an on-site Emergency Response Team that responds to significant chemical incidents.  The team is trained to administer the specialized, medically-approved HF first aid protocols.\n\nThe facility's EAP establishes a written procedure to follow during a major chemical release.  The procedur"
